com.knitting.jamacoi
Class Regression

java.lang.Object
  com.knitting.jamacoi.Regression

public class Regression
extends java.lang.Object

This class implements the standard least squares analysis on the supplied retangular data matrix. This class provides the algebraic muscle to calculate:

1) the estimated equation of coefficients.
2) the analysis of errors.
3) test of significance at different levels of confidence.

This class provides simple reporting capabilities via its "get" and "print" methods. More usable and more meaningful reporting is provided by the Report_Regression_Results class.

Constructor Detail

Regression

public Regression(Sub_Matrix sub_matrix)
           throws not_enough_rows
This method builds most of the needed interminate results for the regression object. These results can be very time consuming to calculate as the amount of data grows. This method requires a rectangular matrix of double values. The most common method of supplying this rectangular matrix is to use the Rectangular_CVS_Matrix class. The rectangular input matrix consists of two logical parts:

1) the first column must be the dependent variable referred traditionally to as Y;
2) multiple other columns which represent the independent variables referred traditionally,in whole, to as X.

Symbolically the rectangular input matrix is: YX

Throws:
not_enough_rows

estimate_coefficients

public void estimate_coefficients(double min_determinate)
                           throws not_enough_rows,
                                  not_invertable,
                                  not_significant
This method attempts to calculate all of the regression results, if possible. The supplied data may prevent the results from being calculated. The supplied data must have specific properties to allow the results to be calculated. If the supplied data does not have these required properties, this method will throw appropriate exceptions to alert the caller of any problem. This method calculates the following results:

1) the inverse matrix to the variance-covariance matrix.
2) the vector of estimated coefficients for the independent variables.
3) the estimated regression intercept.
4) the amount of total sum squared error deviations explained by the the independent variables.
5) the F-value result of the regression which is a measure of the significance of the regression.

Parameters:
min_determinate - is a double field. The purpose of this field is to prevent the degeneration of the analysis because the analysis produced a determinate value that was smaller than this parameter. When the determinate is too small, the results cannot be relied upon. A small determinate will produce results similar to dividing by a number close to zero. A reasonable starting value for this parameter is 1.0E-05
Throws:
not_enough_rows
not_invertable
not_significant

print_Y_dev

public void print_Y_dev()
This method prints the Y deviation matrix: Y_dev. The Y_dev matrix is related to the rectangular input matrix, YX, as follows:

Let: 
       Y_ave = (sum_of_all Y's)/(number_of_rows in YX), then
 
Y_dev(row,1) = [ Y(row,1) - Y_ave ]

print_X_dev

public void print_X_dev()
This method prints the X deviation matrix: X_dev. The X_dev matrix is related to the rectangular input matrix, YX, as follows:

Let: 
    X_ave(col) = (sum_of_all X's in column = col)/(number_of_rows in YX), then
 
X_dev(row,col) = [ X(row,col) - X_ave(col) ]

print_t_X_dev

public void print_t_X_dev()
This method prints the tranpose of the X deviation matrix: t_X_dev. The t_X_dev matrix is related to the rectangular input matrix, YX, as follows:

Let: 
1)      X_ave(col) = (sum_of_all X's in column = col)/(number_of_rows in YX) and
 
2)  X_dev(row,col) = [ X(row,col) - X_ave(col) ], then 

t_X_dev(row,col) = X_dev(col,row)

print_p_XX_dev

public void print_p_XX_dev()
This method prints the product of two matrixs: the tranpose of the X deviation matrix and the X deviation matrix: p_XX_dev. The p_XX_dev matrix is related to the rectangular input matrix, YX, as follows:

Let: 
1)      X_ave(col) = (sum_of_all X's in column = col)/(number_of_rows in YX) and
 
2)  X_dev(row,col) = [ X(row,col) - X_ave(col) ], then 
3)t_X_dev(row,col) = X_dev(col,row)
 
          p_XX_dev = [t_X_dev][X_dev]

print_t_XY_dev

public void print_t_XY_dev()
This method prints the product of two matrixs: the tranpose of the X deviation matrix and the Y deviation matrix: t_XY_dev. The t_XY_dev matrix is related to the rectangular input matrix, YX, as follows:

Let: 
1)      X_ave(col) = (sum_of_all X's in column = col)/(number_of_rows in YX) and
 
2)  X_dev(row,col) = [ X(row,col) - X_ave(col) ]
 
3)t_X_dev(row,col) = X_dev(col,row)
 
4)           Y_ave = (sum_of_all Y's)/(number_of_rows in YX)
 
5)    Y_dev(row,1) = [ Y(row,1) - Y_ave ], then
 
          t_XY_dev = [t_X_dev][Y_dev]

get_det_XX_dev

public double get_det_XX_dev()
This method prints the deteminate of the product of two matrixs:

the 1) transpose of the X deviation matrix, and
2) the X deviation matrix:

det_XX_dev. The t_X_dev matrix and the X_dev matrix are related to the rectangular input matrix, YX, as follows:

Let: 
1)      X_ave(col) = (sum_of_all X's in column = col)/(number_of_rows in YX) and
 
2)  X_dev(row,col) = [ X(row,col) - X_ave(col) ]
 
3)t_X_dev(row,col) = X_dev(col,row)
 
        det_XX_dev = det | [t_X_dev][Y_dev] | 

where   dey_XX_dev is a scalar value and NOT a matrix.
